se poetic culture was undergoing a fundamental transformation, and the stakes were high: the future of modern Japanese verse. Mehl documents the creation of new Japanese poetic forms, tracing the first invention of Japanese free verse and its subsequent disappearance. He examines the impact of the acclaimed and reviled shintaishi, a new poetic form invented for translating European-language verse and eventually supplanted by the reintroduction of free verse as a Western import. The Ends of Meter in Modern Japanese Poetry draws on materials written in German, Spanish, English, and French, recreating the global poetry culture within which the most ambitious Meiji-era Japanese poets vied for position.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aJapanese literaturexForeign influencesxHistoryy19th century. 0aJapanese poetryyMeiji period, 1868-1912xHistory and criticism. 0aTranslating and interpretingzJapanxHistoryy19th century. 4aAsian Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPoetry & Criticism. 7aPOETRY / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh  aMeiji-era Japanese poets, shintaishi, modern Japanese free-verse poetry, nineteenth-century Japanese translations of European poetry, types of japanese poetry,.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107390840 cprintz978150176117140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501761195?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501761195423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501761195/original  a978-3-11-073908-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK